appeared, through the latter 1930s, when they were "Aryanized" by the Nazis. German responses to consumer culture and the Jewish question were deeply interwoven, and the "Jewish department store," framed as an alternative and threatening secular temple, a shrine to commerce and greed, was held responsible for fundamental changes that transformed urban experience and challenged national traditions in Germany’s turbulent twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aConsumer behaviorzGermanyxHistory. 0aConsumption (Economics)zGermanyxHistory. 0aDepartment storeszGermanyxHistory. 0aJewszGermanyxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aJewszGermanyxSocial conditionsy20th century. 4aEurope. 4aHistory.  aCultural consumption, social innovation, German cultual beliefs, Jewish culture, consumer culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170012540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501700125423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501700125/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles